      <memberdef kind="variable" id="structcounter__alarm__cfg__64_1ad7c6734da16d45988fb826b6661607bd" prot="public" static="no" mutable="no">
        <type><ref refid="stdint_8h_1a2095b9bffea4b2656950c6c0419edbf1" kindref="member">uint64_t</ref></type>
        <definition>uint64_t counter_alarm_cfg_64::ticks</definition>
        <argsstring></argsstring>
        <name>ticks</name>
        <qualifiedname>counter_alarm_cfg_64::ticks</qualifiedname>
        <briefdescription>
<para>Number of ticks that triggers the alarm. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>It can be relative (to now) or an absolute value (see <ref refid="group__counter__interface_1ga4842d212424f92c5a3b39116ec6c2fd2" kindref="member">COUNTER_ALARM_CFG_ABSOLUTE</ref>). Both, relative and absolute, alarm values can be any value between zero and the current top value (see <ref refid="group__counter__interface_1ga13d14903a03ab10062002a81b8302424" kindref="member">counter_get_top_value</ref>). When setting an absolute alarm value close to the current counter value there is a risk that the counter will have counted past the given absolute value before the driver manages to activate the alarm. Therefore a guard period can be defined that lets the driver decide unambiguously whether it is late or not (see <ref refid="group__counter__interface_1gab6851411dabf191d3391715d632111b0" kindref="member">counter_set_guard_period</ref>). If the counter is clock driven then ticks can be converted to microseconds (see <ref refid="group__counter__interface_1ga9fbcb710091084e638c45f62c25d954c" kindref="member">counter_ticks_to_us</ref>). Alternatively, the counter implementation may count asynchronous events. </para>
        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
        </inbodydescription>
